  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "zqCOeLyQgk8M2chJ/D8jT92M5gY=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:31.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "Size breakdown for Alice \u2014 1 drive, 5 documents, ~100 operations total:\n\n**PGlite (~60 KB)**\n- Operations: ~100 rows x ~500 bytes = 50 KB\n- Documents: ~5 rows x ~2 KB = 10 KB\n- Relationships: ~5 rows x ~100 bytes = 0.5 KB\n\n**Swarm /bytes (encrypted) (~58 KB)**\n- Operation batches: ~100 ops in ~5 batches x ~10 KB = 50 KB\n- Doc manifests: 5 x ~1 KB = 5 KB\n- Drive manifest: 1 x ~2 KB = 2 KB\n- User manifest: 1 x ~1 KB = 1 KB\n\n**Swarm feeds (~768 bytes)**\n- User feed: 1 x 64 bytes\n- Drive feed: 1 x 64 bytes\n- Doc feeds: 5 x ~2 indices x 64 bytes = 640 bytes\n\n**IndexedDB (~700 bytes)**\n- Manifest index: ~500 bytes\n- Pending ops: 0 (flushed)\n- Signer key: ~200 bytes\n\n**Grand total: ~120 KB**\n- True duplication (ops in both PGlite and Swarm): ~50 KB\n- Metadata overhead (manifests, feeds, caches): ~10 KB \u2014 this is not duplication, it's what enables recovery and lookup\n\n**Takeaway**: at typical scale, duplication is small in absolute terms (~50 KB per user) and the metadata overhead pays for self-sovereignty and recoverability.",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:31.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:31.000Z"
    }
  },
